Produced by @BrianSkerry 
Surface footage by @NansenWeber - Underwater footage by @BrianSkerry

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on July 30, 2021. May be an image of body of water.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

A curious gray seal swims up close to check me out in the waters of the Gulf of Maine. Reminded me of my Labrador retriever at home!

Seals were almost eliminated in New England in the 1800s with seal bounty hunts. Populations in this region have increased substantially since the Marine Mammal Protection Act was signed into law in the US in 1972. 

On assignment for @natgeo  #GulfofMaine #nikonnofilter

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on July 25, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

A humpback whale calf gets a ride on mom’s back in the waters of the South Pacific.

The bond between mother and calf is strong and during the first year of it’s life, the little whale will learn all the skills needed to survive from mom. New research reveals that humpback whale mothers will whisper to their calves in order to remain stealthy when swimming through places where predators are found.

Coverage from ’Secrets of the Whales’ - The Emmy nominated documentary series by @natgeotv streaming now on @disneyplus and my new book of the same name.

#SecretsoftheWhales #humpbackwhales #EmmyAwards

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on July 18, 2021.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

A Giant Squid (Architeuthis) floats dead near the ocean surface in the Azores.

I found this squid during fieldwork on 'Secrets of the Whales.' 
We were in this location working with sperm whales and this squid had fallen out of the mouth of one of the whales. 

Thanks to @moniceph.azores for their valuable science work on identifying the squid species.

#SecretsoftheWhales #giantsquid #nikonnofilter #nikonlove

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on July 02, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry
 
Beluga whales socialize in shallow water in the Canadian Arctic.
 
This population of belugas travel hundreds of kilometers each year to arrive at their ‘summer resort’ where they play for weeks in the midnight sun. Females also give birth in this estuary habitat where the water is a few degrees warmer than the open sea.
 
New photo technology that we designed and built offers a window into the world of these beautiful whales living near the top of planet. A world that is changing rapidly with the decline of sea ice and warming temperatures.
 
Coverage from my latest project, ‘Secrets of the Whales.’
 
#belugawhales #arctic #climatechange

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on June 07, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry
 
Happy World Oceans Day!
 
• We Live On An Ocean Planet
 
• Every Other Breath We Take Comes From The Sea
 
• Our Health & Future is Directly Tied to the Ocean
 
Yet in the last several decades, we have:
 
• Taken 90% of the Large, Predatory Fish
 
• Lost 50% of the World’s Coral Reefs
 
• Put So Much Carbon Into the Atmosphere, The Ocean’s Chemistry is Becoming Acidic
 
• Dumped 18 Billion Pounds of Plastic into the Sea Annually
 
We take so much out of the sea and put so many dangerous things into the sea.
 
On this day - Let us pause to think about how much better we can do to protect Earth’s oceans.
 
Our future and the future of our children depend on this.  #worldoceansday

Produced by @BrianSkerry

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on May 27, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

An Orca works to corral a massive bait ball of herring in the winter seas of the Norwegian arctic.  Orca come here to feed on these fish in the fall and stay into the polar winter when the sun no longer rises above the horizon and light levels are extremely low.  The Orca use communication and coordination to gather the fish into ‘bait balls’ then swim through, stunning the herring with their tails before eating them.  Creating unique feeding strategies demonstrates a high degree of cognition and is a key element of whale and dolphin culture.

Coverage from my new book ‘Secrets of the Whales’ - available wherever books are sold.

Secrets of the Whales’ is also a new, 4-part documentary series now streaming on @disneyplus and a cover story in the May issue of National Geographic magazine @natgeo 

#secretsofthewhales 
#nikonnofilter #nikonlove 
#orca

node.text:
Recently, I delivered the Commencement Address to the 2021 Graduating Class of Worcester State University in Massachusetts. @worcesterstate 

This was not only a great honor, but was also deeply gratifying to share my thoughts on the things that most enrich our lives.

You can watch my address by clicking the YouTube link in my profile.

Thank you the WSU class of 2021 for inviting me to speak. And thank you to WSU’s President Maloney and the University’s Board for awarding me the degree of Doctor of Humane Letters, honoris causa.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

A Sperm Whale calf nurses from its mom in the waters of the Eastern Caribbean Sea. 

In the time that I have spent with these animals, I have been amazed at their tenderness to one another. Most of sperm whale lives are spent in the deep, dark and cold sea and they seem to truly relish these social gatherings in shallow water. 
What I have observed can only be described as joy when they socialize with each other.

Coverage from my new book ‘Secrets of the Whales’ - available wherever books are sold.

’Secrets of the Whales’ is also a new, 4-part documentary series now streaming on @disneyplus and a cover story in the May issue of National Geographic magazine @natgeo 

With @shanegero 
#SecretsoftheWhales #nikonnofilter #nikonlove

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry

A group of beluga whales play and socialize in shallow coastal waters in the Canadian high-arctic. Beluga families travel hundreds of miles each summer to spend time at their ‘summer playground’ - a location where a river flows into the sea. Water temperatures here are slightly warmer here than the 29-degree Fahrenheit ocean water temperatures, which is ideal for newborn calves.  The gravel bottom here also serves as a natural loofa on which they rub to remove old skin. 

Coverage from my new book ‘Secrets of the Whales’ - available wherever books are sold.

In my book I share my experiences with whales, from the challenges of whale photography and life in the field to the cultures and personalities of individual whales.

’Secrets of the Whales’ is also a new, 4-part documentary series now streaming on @disneyplus and a cover story in the May issue of National Geographic magazine @natgeo 

With @nansenweber 
#SecretsoftheWhales #belugawhales #whales #arctic

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brian Skerry on May 09, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @BrianSkerry 

Happy Mother’s Day - To loving moms everywhere that are always watching over their children!

I spent time with this humpback whale mom & calf early one morning in the waters off of Tonga in the Pacific. Watching them nuzzle and play together remains one of my most special memories of time in nature.
